<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 3 — Evaluating Arguments: Validity and Strength
  First full draft.

  Scope:
  - The two questions one asks when evaluating an argument.
  - Validity and soundness (deductive standard).
  - Four valid forms with worked instances: MP, MT, DS, HS.
  - Two invalid forms: affirming the consequent, denying the antecedent.
  - The counterexample method.
  - Inductive strength and cogency (the inductive parallels).
  - Forward pivot to Parts II–IV for the formal machinery.

  Voice: matter-of-fact, declarative, second-person where it lands,
  real-world examples (politically-current where they land), dry humor
  reserved for parentheticals. Continues the "is this any good?" thread.

  Not yet introduced (deferred to later chapters):
  - Venn diagrams (Part II)
  - Truth tables (Part III)
  - Natural deduction proofs (Part III)
  - Statistical inference (Part IV)
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-evaluating-arguments">

  <title>Evaluating Arguments: Validity and Strength</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-evaluating-arguments-intro">
    <p>
      Chapters 1 and 2 taught two skills: recognizing arguments in
      real prose, and reconstructing them carefully. We can now look
      at an argument with its premises and conclusion clearly laid
      out, and a support note saying which premises support which
      conclusions and how.
    </p>
    <p>
      The next question is the one we have been asking from the
      beginning: <em>is this argument any good?</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter introduces the vocabulary we need to ask that
      question precisely. We will not yet have the formal machinery
      that lets us answer it for arbitrary arguments — that work
      begins in the next chapter and continues through the rest of
      the book. What we build here is the conceptual frame: what is
      being asked when we ask whether an argument is good, what
      counts as a good answer, and how the question splits along the
      deductive/inductive divide we first met in
      <xref ref="sec-language"/>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-two-questions">
    <title>The Two Questions</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        When you ask whether an argument is good, you are really
        asking two distinct questions, and they are independent of
        each other.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-questions-statement">
      <title>What the two questions are</title>
      <p>
        The first question is: do the premises actually support the
        conclusion? If you accept the premises, do you have to accept
        the conclusion (or, for inductive arguments, do you have good
        reason to)?
      </p>
      <p>
        The second question is: are the premises actually true?
      </p>
      <p>
        Both questions matter. An argument that fails on the first
        question is broken structurally — even if every sentence in
        it happened to be true, the conclusion would not follow from
        the premises. An argument that fails on the second question
        may have perfectly good structure, but the case it makes
        rests on something false.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-two-questions-independent">
      <title>The two questions are independent</title>
      <p>
        An argument can have false premises but a structure where the
        conclusion would follow if the premises were true. Or it can
        have all true premises but a structure where the conclusion
        does not follow at all. Or it can be perfect on both fronts.
        Or perfect on neither. Each combination is possible, and each
        gives us different information about how to engage with the
        argument.
      </p>
      <p>
        Logic begins with the first question — the structural one.
        The technical machinery of categorical logic, sentential
        logic, and natural deduction (the work of Parts II and III
        of this book) is, fundamentally, machinery for answering
        whether premises support conclusions. The second question is
        not abandoned: premises matter, and a beautiful structural
        argument from false premises is not a good argument. But the
        second question is mostly about the world, not about logic,
        and the logical work for the inductive case lives in
        statistical reasoning (Part IV) where the relationship
        between evidence and claims is what is at stake.
      </p>
      <p>
        Before we can do any of that work, though, we need names for
        the two situations: where the structure is good, and where
        the structure is good and the premises are also true. The
        names depend on whether the argument is deductive or
        inductive. We take the deductive case first.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-validity-soundness">
    <title>Validity and Soundness</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A deductive argument is meant to do a specific thing:
        guarantee its conclusion if its premises are true. The
        technical name for an argument that achieves that guarantee
        is <term>valid</term>.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-validity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An argument is <term>valid</term> when, if its premises are
          true, its conclusion must also be true. There is no
          instance of the argument's form in which the premises are
          all true and the conclusion is false.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-validity-is-structural">
      <title>Validity is a structural property</title>
      <p>
        Validity depends on the form of the argument, not on whether
        the premises or conclusion happen to be true. An argument can
        be valid even if its premises are false. It can be valid even
        if its conclusion is false. What makes it valid is that the
        structure makes the conclusion forced <em>given</em> the
        premises.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-valid-elections">
        <title>A valid argument with arguably true premises</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: If a country has free and fair elections, then its citizens can vote out incumbents who fail them.</p>
          <p>P2: This country has free and fair elections.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Its citizens can vote out incumbents who fail them.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This argument is valid. The structure is: if P then Q; P;
        therefore Q. If you accept both premises, you cannot deny
        the conclusion without contradicting yourself. Whether
        either premise is <em>actually</em> true in any particular
        country is a separate question, and a serious one. The
        validity of the argument does not turn on the answer.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-valid-moon-cheese">
        <title>A valid argument with obviously false premises</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: If the moon is made of cheese, then mice love astronauts.</p>
          <p>P2: The moon is made of cheese.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Mice love astronauts.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Both premises are clearly false. The argument is still valid.
        The structure is the same as the previous example: if P then
        Q; P; therefore Q. If both premises were true, the conclusion
        would have to be true. Validity does not care about reality;
        it cares about the relation between premises and conclusion.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <definition xml:id="def-soundness">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An argument is <term>sound</term> when it is valid <em>and</em>
          all its premises are actually true.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-soundness-discussion">
      <title>Soundness combines structure and substance</title>
      <p>
        A sound argument has a true conclusion, because validity
        forces it. So a sound argument is the gold standard:
        structurally good, substantively grounded, conclusion
        guaranteed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sound arguments are rarer than they sound. Most real-world
        deductive arguments are valid in form but rest on premises
        whose truth is contestable. That doesn't make the arguments
        useless. Knowing an argument is valid tells you where to
        push back: if you cannot accept the conclusion, you must
        reject at least one premise. Validity hands you the leverage
        point. If a friend offers you a valid argument for a
        conclusion you find unpalatable, your honest options are to
        accept the conclusion, identify a premise you can deny, or
        admit you have not yet decided. <q>I just don't like it</q>
        is not on the list.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-some-valid-forms">
    <title>Some Valid Forms</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Validity belongs to the form of an argument, not its content.
        The same form, with different content, has the same validity
        status. There are a small number of forms that come up over
        and over in everyday and formal reasoning. We meet four of
        them now. They will reappear, formally, in Part III, where
        natural deduction will turn each into a named inference rule.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-mp">
      <title>Modus Ponens</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-mp-form">
        <title>Modus Ponens (MP)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Schema:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If P, then Q.</p>
          <p>P2: P.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Q.</p>
          <p><alert>Instance:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If we expand the grid, we can keep up with new data center demand.</p>
          <p>P2: We expand the grid.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: We can keep up with new data center demand.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Modus ponens</term> — Latin, roughly <q>the way that
        affirms</q> — is the most basic conditional inference. From a
        conditional and the affirmation of its antecedent, we
        conclude the affirmation of its consequent. We met this form
        already in <xref ref="sec-premises-conclusions"/> when we
        looked at the modus-ponens argument from the existence of
        evil to the conclusion that God does not exist.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-mt">
      <title>Modus Tollens</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-mt-form">
        <title>Modus Tollens (MT)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Schema:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If P, then Q.</p>
          <p>P2: Not Q.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Not P.</p>
          <p><alert>Instance:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If a candidate had stronger turnout in this district, they would have won.</p>
          <p>P2: They did not win.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: They did not have stronger turnout in this district.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Modus tollens</term> — <q>the way that denies</q> —
        runs the conditional in reverse. From a conditional and the
        denial of its consequent, we conclude the denial of its
        antecedent. We met this form too, in
        <xref ref="sec-premises-conclusions"/>: the modus tollens
        argument from <q>life is not meaningless</q> to the
        conclusion that God exists.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ds">
      <title>Disjunctive Syllogism</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-ds-form">
        <title>Disjunctive Syllogism (DS)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Schema:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: P or Q.</p>
          <p>P2: Not P.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Q.</p>
          <p><alert>Instance:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: Either the city expands transit or rush hour gets worse.</p>
          <p>P2: The city did not expand transit.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Rush hour got worse.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Disjunctive syllogism</term> takes a disjunction (an
        <em>or</em>-statement) and the denial of one disjunct to
        conclude the other. The argument works equally well in the
        other direction: from <q>P or Q</q> and <q>not Q</q>, conclude
        <q>P</q>. The Field Exercise in
        <xref ref="sec-premises-conclusions"/> on oil subsidies and
        political theater was a disjunctive syllogism.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-hs">
      <title>Hypothetical Syllogism</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-hs-form">
        <title>Hypothetical Syllogism (HS)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Schema:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If P, then Q.</p>
          <p>P2: If Q, then R.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: If P, then R.</p>
          <p><alert>Instance:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If interest rates fall, then borrowing increases.</p>
          <p>P2: If borrowing increases, then construction picks up.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: If interest rates fall, then construction picks up.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Hypothetical syllogism</term> chains conditionals: from
        <q>if P then Q</q> and <q>if Q then R</q>, we conclude <q>if
        P then R</q>. The conclusion is itself a conditional, not a
        free-standing claim. This matters when reading real
        arguments: a hypothetical syllogism doesn't entitle you to
        assert R outright, only the conditional connecting P to R.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-four-forms-summary">
      <title>Four forms, one observation</title>
      <p>
        All four forms are valid by their structure alone. Substitute
        any P, Q, R you like — sentences about elections, about
        weather, about whether your roommate did the dishes — and
        the validity holds. We will see all four in Part III as named
        inference rules in the natural deduction system. For now,
        recognizing them in everyday reasoning is itself a real
        skill, and it is what most of the practice in this chapter
        is about.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-invalid-forms-counterexamples">
    <title>Two Invalid Forms and the Counterexample Method</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Not every argument that <em>looks</em> like a valid form is
        one. Two forms are easy to mistake for the valid ones we
        just met. They are not valid, and recognizing them is as
        important as recognizing the valid forms. Confusing them is
        one of the most common reasoning errors in real arguments,
        and being able to spot it is a useful skill in its own
        right.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-affirming-consequent">
      <title>Affirming the consequent</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-affirming-consequent">
        <title>Affirming the consequent (invalid)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Schema:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If P, then Q.</p>
          <p>P2: Q.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: P.</p>
          <p><alert>Instance:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If it is raining, the streets are wet.</p>
          <p>P2: The streets are wet.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: It is raining.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Affirming the consequent</term> looks like modus ponens
        with the second premise flipped. From a conditional and the
        affirmation of its consequent, the argument concludes the
        affirmation of its antecedent. That is not a valid move.
      </p>
      <p>
        Why not? The conditional <q>if P then Q</q> tells us that P
        is <em>one</em> way to get Q. It does not tell us P is the
        <em>only</em> way. Q might be true for some other reason
        entirely. Concluding P from Q ignores that possibility.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the streets-and-rain instance, the streets might be wet
        because a sprinkler ran for an hour, or a water main broke,
        or someone washed their car. The conditional is still true
        (if it <em>were</em> raining, the streets <em>would</em> be
        wet). The conclusion just doesn't follow.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-denying-antecedent">
      <title>Denying the antecedent</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-denying-antecedent">
        <title>Denying the antecedent (invalid)</title>
        <statement>
          <p><alert>Schema:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If P, then Q.</p>
          <p>P2: Not P.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Not Q.</p>
          <p><alert>Instance:</alert></p>
          <p>P1: If you study every night, you'll do well on the exam.</p>
          <p>P2: You did not study every night.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: You will not do well on the exam.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        <term>Denying the antecedent</term> looks like modus tollens
        with the second premise flipped. The argument denies the
        antecedent rather than the consequent. Also not valid.
      </p>
      <p>
        Same reason as before: P is one way to Q, not the only way.
        Just because P does not happen does not mean Q cannot.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the studying-and-exam instance, the conclusion does not
        follow. You could do well anyway — maybe you already knew the
        material, or you studied differently, or you got lucky on the
        questions, or the exam was easy. The conditional describes
        one path to a good outcome, not the only one.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-counterexample-method">
      <title>The counterexample method</title>
      <p>
        The general way to show that an argument form is invalid is
        to construct a <term>counterexample</term>: an instance of
        the form in which the premises are all true and the
        conclusion is false. If even one such instance exists, the
        form fails — because validity requires that <em>no</em>
        instance has true premises and a false conclusion.
      </p>
      <p>
        Building a counterexample is the work we just did. We took
        the form <q>If P, then Q. Q. <m>\therefore</m> P.</q> and
        substituted content where the premises came out true and the
        conclusion came out false. The streets are wet because the
        sprinkler ran. The conditional <q>if it is raining, the
        streets are wet</q> is true. The premise <q>the streets are
        wet</q> is true. The conclusion <q>it is raining</q> is
        false. That single counterexample is enough to settle the
        form's invalidity.
      </p>
      <p>
        A few things to notice. First, the counterexample doesn't
        need to be realistic — it just has to be possible. We could
        write down something silly, as long as the premises came out
        true and the conclusion false; the form would still be
        invalidated. (Realistic counterexamples are usually more
        persuasive in conversation, but for logic, possibility is
        enough.) Second, a counterexample to the form invalidates
        the form, not just one instance. If we have shown that <q>If
        P, then Q. Q. <m>\therefore</m> P.</q> can have true
        premises with a false conclusion, we have shown that
        <em>any</em> argument of that form is invalid, regardless of
        the content of P and Q. Third, if you cannot find a
        counterexample after honest effort, that is not yet proof of
        validity — formal validity proofs come later. But the
        difficulty of finding a counterexample is at least evidence
        that the form may be valid. Subsequent chapters' machinery
        confirms or disconfirms the suspicion.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-strength-cogency">
    <title>Inductive Strength and Cogency</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Validity belongs to deductive arguments — arguments where the
        premises are meant to <em>guarantee</em> the conclusion. Many
        real arguments are not like that. They are inductive:
        arguments where the premises make the conclusion <em>more
        likely</em>, but not guaranteed. We met this distinction in
        <xref ref="sec-language"/>; now we name the standards by
        which inductive arguments are evaluated.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-strength">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An inductive argument is <term>strong</term> when, if its
          premises are all true, its conclusion is much more likely
          to be true than not. Strength is a matter of degree: an
          inductive argument can be very strong, moderately strong,
          weak, or somewhere in between.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-strength-discussion">
      <title>Strength is a matter of degree</title>
      <p>
        Unlike validity, strength is not all-or-nothing. A deductive
        argument is either valid or it is not — there is no such
        thing as <q>more valid.</q> But an inductive argument can
        be moderately strong, very strong, or weak. The premises
        push the probability of the conclusion in some direction by
        some amount; the question is how much.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-strong-inductive">
        <title>A strong inductive argument</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: All twelve patients in the trial who received the vaccine produced antibodies.</p>
          <p>P2: The patients in the trial were a representative sample of the broader population.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: The vaccine probably produces antibodies in the broader population.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        If the premises are true, the conclusion is significantly
        more likely than it would be otherwise. The conclusion is
        not forced — sample sizes can mislead, populations vary,
        twelve is small — but the support is real and substantial.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-weak-inductive">
        <title>A weak inductive argument</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: My friend Alex got sick after eating at the cafeteria.</p>
          <p>P2: Alex is one person.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: The cafeteria is unsanitary.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The premises do support the conclusion <em>slightly</em> —
        there's some increase in probability — but not enough to draw
        the conclusion responsibly. One person could get sick for
        many reasons; one observation is not a pattern. We will be
        much more careful about the difference between weak and
        strong inductive evidence in Part IV, where statistical
        reasoning is the main subject.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <definition xml:id="def-cogency">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An inductive argument is <term>cogent</term> when it is
          strong <em>and</em> all its premises are actually true.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cogency-discussion">
      <title>Cogency is the inductive parallel to soundness</title>
      <p>
        Cogency is to inductive arguments what soundness is to
        deductive arguments: the structural standard plus a
        substantive one. A cogent argument is a strong inductive
        argument whose premises are also true. Cogent arguments give
        you good reason — not certain, but good — to accept their
        conclusions.
      </p>
      <p>
        The two evaluations track each other:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>For deductive: <em>validity</em> (structure) plus true premises gives <em>soundness</em>.</p></li>
        <li><p>For inductive: <em>strength</em> (structure, in degree) plus true premises gives <em>cogency</em>.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Same shape: a structural property plus a substantive one.
        Both questions live in every argument; the names just change
        depending on whether we're being asked to <em>guarantee</em>
        the conclusion or only to <em>raise its probability</em>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-where-headed-ch3">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        This chapter built the vocabulary. It did not build the
        procedures.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-ch3-summary">
      <title>What this chapter gave us</title>
      <p>
        We can now ask <q>is this argument any good?</q> with
        structure. We have names for the four situations one finds
        in real arguments: valid and sound (the deductive gold
        standard); valid but unsound (structurally fine, but resting
        on a false premise — push back on the premise); strong and
        cogent (the inductive gold standard); and strong but
        uncogent (good inductive structure on shaky factual ground —
        same problem, different domain). We have four valid
        deductive forms, two invalid forms that look like them, and
        the counterexample method as the basic test for invalidity.
      </p>
      <p>
        What we don't yet have are general procedures for evaluating
        arbitrary arguments. We have hand-classified a handful of
        forms in this chapter. The rest of the book builds the
        machinery for doing this work systematically.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-where-headed-ch3-pivot">
      <title>What's coming</title>
      <p>
        The chapters that follow build that machinery in different
        domains.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Part II: categorical logic.</alert> Venn diagrams
            will let us evaluate arguments built from categorical
            statements (<q>All As are Bs</q>, <q>No As are Bs</q>,
            <q>Some As are Bs</q>, <q>Some As are not Bs</q>). This
            is the natural home for the syllogisms first studied by
            Aristotle, and it is the machinery for an important
            class of everyday arguments.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Part III: sentential logic.</alert> Truth tables
            will let us evaluate arguments built out of compound
            statements connected by <em>and</em>, <em>or</em>,
            <em>not</em>, <em>if-then</em>, and <em>if and only
            if</em>. Natural deduction will let us prove validity by
            chaining inference rules from a small starter set. The
            four valid forms in <xref ref="sec-some-valid-forms"/>
            reappear there as named rules.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Part IV: inductive and statistical reasoning.</alert>
            The strength evaluation gets a serious workout here,
            where statistical inference, probability, and reasoning
            under uncertainty become the main tools. Cogency is the
            standard those tools are computing.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Validity and soundness, strength and cogency, are the
        standards each of those domains is computing. The technical
        chapters give us the procedures; this chapter named what the
        procedures are for.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch3">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch3-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identifying Valid Forms</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each argument, identify which of the four valid forms
          (modus ponens, modus tollens, disjunctive syllogism,
          hypothetical syllogism) it instantiates.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>If the bridge is open, the commute takes thirty minutes. The bridge is open. So the commute takes thirty minutes.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>If the proposal had cleared committee, the chair would have announced it. The chair did not announce it. So the proposal did not clear committee.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Either the data center applies for a new permit or the construction stops. The data center did not apply for a new permit. So construction stops.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>If turnout is above sixty percent, the incumbent wins. If the incumbent wins, the policy continues. So if turnout is above sixty percent, the policy continues.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch3-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Spotting Invalid Forms</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each of the following arguments looks like a valid form
          but is actually an instance of affirming the consequent or
          denying the antecedent. For each, identify which invalid
          form it is.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <p>If a senator is corrupt, they accept dark-money donations. Senator X accepts dark-money donations. So Senator X is corrupt.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <p>If a student attends every class, they will pass the course. This student did not attend every class. So this student will not pass the course.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <p>If a country has a stable currency, foreign investment increases. Foreign investment in this country has increased. So this country has a stable currency.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s02-04">
        <statement>
          <p>If the medication works, the patient's symptoms improve. The medication did not work. So the patient's symptoms will not improve.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch3-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Constructing Counterexamples</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each invalid form below, construct a counterexample —
          an instance of the form with all premises true and the
          conclusion false. Briefly explain why your counterexample
          works.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The form <em>affirming the consequent</em>: If P, then Q. Q. <m>\therefore</m> P.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The form <em>denying the antecedent</em>: If P, then Q. Not P. <m>\therefore</m> Not Q.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Consider the form <q>All As are Bs. All Bs are Cs. <m>\therefore</m> All Cs are As.</q> Construct a counterexample showing that this form is invalid.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch3-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Validity, Soundness, or Neither</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each argument, decide whether it is (a) valid and
          sound, (b) valid but unsound, or (c) invalid. Briefly
          justify your answer. You may need to evaluate the truth of
          a premise; for arguments where reasonable people disagree,
          say so.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>If two plus two equals four, then arithmetic works as we have learned it. Two plus two equals four. So arithmetic works as we have learned it.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>All cats are reptiles. All reptiles lay eggs. So all cats lay eggs.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>If the moon orbits the Earth, then tides exist. The moon orbits the Earth. So tides exist.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <p>If a piece of legislation is bipartisan, then it must be reasonable. The bill in question was bipartisan. So the bill in question must be reasonable.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch3-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Strength and Cogency</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each inductive argument, decide whether it is strong
          or weak, and whether you have enough information to judge
          cogency. Briefly explain.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s05-01">
        <statement>
          <p>Of the last hundred winters in this region, ninety-three had at least one significant snowfall. So this winter will probably have at least one significant snowfall.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s05-02">
        <statement>
          <p>One person I know got food poisoning from a particular restaurant. So that restaurant is unsafe.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s05-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Eighty percent of small businesses surveyed reported that the new ordinance increased their costs. The survey was sent to a representative sample. So the new ordinance probably increases costs for small businesses generally.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch3-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Mixed Evaluation</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each argument, identify whether it is deductive or
          inductive; if deductive, evaluate validity (and, where
          possible, soundness); if inductive, evaluate strength (and,
          where possible, cogency). Briefly explain.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s06-01">
        <statement>
          <p>If the city raises the property tax rate, then revenue for schools will increase. The city did raise the property tax rate. So revenue for schools will increase.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s06-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The last three quarterly reports showed declining revenue. So next quarter's report will probably show declining revenue too.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s06-03">
        <statement>
          <p>Either the proposal cleared committee or the chair tabled it. The proposal did not clear committee. So the chair tabled it.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch3-s06-04">
        <statement>
          <p>If a defendant has reasonable doubt established against the prosecution's case, they should be acquitted. Reasonable doubt has been established. So the defendant should be acquitted.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
